title: For Sale:  Glock 21 Longslide   -   Lonewolf parts, CHECK IT OUT!
location: East Side of Cleveland, Cleveland, Ohio
postcontent:
I am the original owner, and it has exactly FIVE rounds through it. I built this weapon myself using all Glock OEM and Lonewolf parts.

I started with a brand new Glock 21 SF frame
I then ordered brand new Lonewolf Glock 21 Longslide slide and threaded barrel. I paid to have the slide and barrel blind-marked and black oxide coated. The barrel is topped with a Sig thread protector.

The slide was completed using all Glock OEM small parts, and the guide rod is a Lonewolf stainless steel guide rod with a Glock 21 spring. The slide also has Trijicon Tritium suppressor sights.

The gun performed great, and was a blast to shoot. The barrel comes in at about 6.5" in length. Definitely not a Glock you see every day.

Comes with 1x Glock OEM 13 round magazine.

All together this cost me about $800 to build. It was a fun project and someone will get a lot of joy out of it. My loss is your gain

Also included is a Midway USA pistol case, and 50x blazer brass .45ACP and 20x Barnes JHP so you can test it out when you take it home.

I am open to trades, just offer.
Buyer must have valid Ohio Driver's License. Valid CCW is preferred.

I have other guns for sale, I would be willing to shave off hundreds of dollars if you purchase multiple items.

title: For Sale:  Norinco NHM90 not NHM91
postcontent: For sale is a rare NHM90 chambered in 7.62.  At the start of the Chinese ban these are the rifles that were being imported before the Mak90. The bayonet lugs where being cut off and a sleeve welded over the muzzle threads to eliminate muzzle brakes.  This one has since had the sleeve removed and been rethreaded.  1.5mm thick, straight cut receiver not the angled. Most of the nhm90's were chambered for 5.56 so its actually quite rare to see one in 7.62.  This is not a NHM 91 variant.   This is just like a Mak90  but  much more  difficult to find. Especially in this caliber.  Great piece to add to a norinco collection or start one! This rifle has all #'s matching. This is one of only two NHM90's for sale on armslist in this caliber.   CASH ONLY. NO TRADES.

postcontent:
You can't find a big-game rifle with a better combination of practical shooting features: twin action bars provide slick, smooth operation for rapid repeat shots; a quick-release, drop-out four-round magazine that loads and unloads instantly; and a free-floated barrel that matches the accuracy of the best bolt guns.

.280 Remington Ballistics
History, Details, Ballistics, and Drop for the .280 Remington




Cartridge Type: Rifle
Height: 2.54"
Width: 0.473"
Average FPS: 2896
Average Energy: 2793
Average Gr: 150
Recoil: 1.95
Power Rank: 4.34 of 20 [?]
The .280 Remington was designed in 1957 by Remington Arms Company for the 700 series rifles. The parent case is a .30-06 Springfield, and is narrowed down to fit the .284 inch (7.2mm) bullet. The semi- automatic 740 was the first rifle Remington used for the .280 factory loads with a psi of 48,000 to 50,000 for 150 grain bullets. The ballistic performances based off five grain types for velocity are 3,112 ft/s (120 gr), 2,839 ft/s (140 gr), 2,825 ft/s (154 gr), 2,723 ft/s (168 gr), 2,681 ft/s (175 gr).
Remington changed the powder charge of the .280 factory load in 1979 and re-named the .280 Remington to the 7mm Express Remington. After some confusion on the market they reversed the name change back to the .280 Remington. The factory loads consist of 140-150 grain cartridges that are best suited for medium sized game.
The .280 factory loads can be used on medium sized game up to 250 yards before a noticeable drop in wound penetration occurs. Hand loading .280 brass can reach 3,100 ft/s (140 gr), 3,000 ft/s (150 gr). They can be suited to lower powder use for varmint hunting, or custom fit on a 26 inch barrel for maximum velocity in hunting medium sized game. Hand loading rounds can reach upwards of 375 yards before a noticeable drop off in wound penetration occurs.

Here's the deal with this gun. I bought it brand new recently. I needed something to pocket carry turns out I don't like pocket carry. 

On my first time shooting the gun, after about 20 rounds, the cylinder locked up and the gun wouldn't fire. I had to open and close the cylinder once to get the gun to fire. I called smith and Wesson and they said it sounded as if there was debris/metal shavings from production inside the action and that it will probably not be a problem. I opened up the side plate, cleaned and lubed the internals. That is the whole history of the gun. Both smith and Wesson and I feel that the problem is resolved, but the price reflects the history. title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 made 1912   4-digit S/N
postcontent:
Early 4-digit Colt model 1911,.45 auto, U.S. Property marked, blued finish, checkered wood grips, serial number 2030. This low serial number remains in good to very good untouched original conditions showing 70% original blue finish, Some erosion, light to very moderate scattered pitting, good markings, grips good with even wear, Markings are all visible and there is some bright finish on small parts and protected areas. The pistol shows all correct early major component parts including ,trigger, hammer, grips, etc. and shows early patent dates, early inspections , and  a later two-tone lanyard bottom magazine. Action good 1911's ,very good.and Colt just shows honest use consistent with military use. These early 1911's went primarily to Texas and the border areas and were used before the First World War along the border in the Pancho Villa era., Which is a sign it has a remarkable military history It would be difficult to fine a more honest and untouched early 4-digit 1911, which has become prohibitively expensive in fine condition. The Colt barrel has markings-C,which might be a WWII . Recorded as one of a group shipped to Springfield Armory April 16th, 1912  1 Of 150 in shipment.

This is a very nice 9mm Astra-A90 Pistol. Compact, High capacity, magazine holds 15 round. All metal gun, everything works great. Cleaned after every range trip. Also comes with about 70 rounds, a mix of hollowpoints, ball ammo and self-defense rounds

Caliber: 9x19mm Luger/Parabellum
Weight Unloaded: 35 oz
Length 7 in
Barrel Length: 3.7in
15 round magazine

Background:
The Astra A-90 pistols was developed by Spanish company Astra-Unceta y Cia SA, in 1985, and is patterned after the Sig Sauer P-220. A-90 features a similar frame and slide shape, similar recoil-operated, locked breech design with improved Browning-style linkless locking and one large lug that locks into the ejection port in the slide. The double action trigger with frame mounted decocker on the left side of the grip is also patterned after the P-220. Another feature that is different from the SIG-Sauer P220 is that the A-90 has a double stack, high capacity magazine.
The A-90 features a two-piece firing pin with firing pin safety that locks frontal part of the pin, plus ambidextrous, slide mounted manual safety, that, when engaged, removed the rear part of the firing pin from the hammer path, regardless the position of the hammer.

title: For Sale:  Yugoslavian 7.62 AK ammo in Sealed Tins - 1260 rounds
postcontent:
I have two sealed tins of 1260 rounds of 7.62x39 Yugoslavian ammo.  Price is for each tin.  Unopened.

Beautiful 1970-90's Surplus Yugoslavian 7.62x39 ammunition. This is the best shooting 7.62x39 ammunition available. Features a 123grn lead core copper jacketed bullet, brass case, and berdan corrosive primer. 1,260rds (84 boxes) sealed in metal tin.

In the 1960s Yugoslavia experimented with new bullet designs to produce a round with a superior wounding profile, speed, and accuracy to the M43. The M67 projectile is shorter and flatter-based than the M43. This is mainly due to the deletion of the mild steel insert. This has the side effect of shifting the center of gravity rearward in comparison to the M43. This allows the projectile to destabilize nearly 17 cm (6.7 in) earlier in tissue. This causes a pair of large stretch cavities at a depth likely to cause effective wound trauma. When the temporary stretch cavity intersects with the skin at the exit area, a larger exit wound will result, which takes longer to heal. Additionally, when the stretch cavity intersects a stiff organ like the liver, it will cause damage to that organ. However, the wounding potential of M67 is mostly limited to the small permanent wound channel the bullet itself makes, especially when the bullet yaws (tumbles).
